definition.value: Any S-conjugate of mycothiol.
An S-substituted N-acetyl-L-cysteine arising from formal 1,4-addition of the side-chain sulfur atom to N-ethylmaleimide.
An organic phosphonic acid derivative in which one or more oxygen atoms of the phosphonate group(s) has been deprotonated.

A phosphatidylinositol mannoside having the phosphatidyl moiety (with specific O-acyl groups) at the 1-position, a single mannosyl residue at the 2-position and a linear pentamannoside at position 6 of the inositol ring.
The S-nitroso derivative of mycothiol.
The sulfinamide of mycothiol.
Isatin bearing a 6-aminohexanamido group at C-5.
A dialdehyde that is cyclopentanecarbaldehyde substituted by a methyl group at position 2 and a 1-methyl-2-oxoethyl group at position 5.
An N-acylglucosamine where the N-acyl group is specified as acetyl.
A glycosylrhamnose consisting of two L-rhamnopyranose units joined by an alpha(1->2) linkage.
The (3-chloro-2-hydroxypropyl) (2,3-dihydroxypropyl) diether of bisphenol A; a small molecule that inhibits transactivation of the AR amino-terminal domain (NTD).

Any fatty acid having at least one of the chain methylene groups replaced by sulfur. Members of this group are believed to have important pharmacological (antioxidant and antiatherosclerosis) properties.
Any fatty acid containing at least one aldehydic or ketonic group in addition to the carboxylic acid group.
A glycopeptidolipid antigen from clinically prominent members of the Mycobacterium avium serocomplex
An EC 2.3.1.* (acyltransferase transferring other than amino-acyl group) inhibitor that interferes with the action of serine palmitoyltransferase (EC 2.3.1.50).
The anion resulting from the removal of the proton from the phosphate group of precursor Z.

A hydrochloride resulting from the formal reacton of equimolar amounts of hydrogen chloride and amorolfine. An inhibitor of the action of squalene monooxygenase, Delta(14) reductase and D7-D8 isomerase and an antifungal agent, it is used for the topical treatment of fungal nail and skin infections.
A fatty acid containing at least one amino substituent.
The dihydrogen arsenothioate resulting from the formal condensation of the thiol group of mycothiol with arsenic acid.
An amino alcohol formed by reduction of the amino acid proline.
The anion resulting from the removal of a proton from the arsenate group of arseno-mycothiol.
The class of all compounds which contain a prolinol skeleton.
The dianion resulting from the removal of both protons from the arsenate group of arseno-mycothiol.
Phosphine oxides are organophosphorus compounds with the formula OPR3, where R = alkyl or aryl. They are considered to be the most stable organophosphorus compounds.
Any organic cation containing a pyrylium skeleton and its substituted derivatives thereof.
Any salt of pyrylium or its derivatives
A sulindac-based non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drug.
A mixture where R = H or Me. The penta-anion resulting from the removal of protons from each of the sulfonic acid groups of colistimethate.

A mixture where R = H or Me. Colistin in which each of the primary amino groups is converted to the corresponding aminomethanesulfonic acid. It is prepared from colistin by the action of formaldehyde followed by sodium bisulfite. A polymyxin antibiotic, it is used as its penta-sodium salt in the treatment of severe infections, particularly of multidrug-resistant Gram-negative bacteria such as Pseudomonas aeruginosa and Acinetobacter baumannii.
Colistin A in which each of the primary amino groups is converted into the corresponding aminomethanesulfonic acid sodium salt, commonly by treatment with formaldehyde followed by sodium bisulfite.
Colistin B in which each of the primary amino groups is converted into the corresponding aminomethanesulfonic acid sodium salt, commonly by treatment with formaldehyde followed by sodium bisulfite.
The penta-anion resulting from the removal of protons from each of the sulfonic acid groups of colistimethate A.
The penta-anion resulting from the removal of protons from each of the sulfonic acid groups of colistimethate B.

A class of nucleoside-peptide antibiotics which inhibit fungal chitin biosynthesis by inhibiting chitin synthase. Generally consist of a heterocyclic moiety (usually a nucleobase), an amino hexuronic acid and an amino acid containing a pyridine ring.
Colistin A in which each of the primary amino groups is converted to the corresponding aminomethanesulfonic acid, commonly by the action of formaldehyde followed by sodium bisulfite.
Colistin B in which each of the primary amino groups is converted into the corresponding aminomethanesulfonic acid, commonly by the action of formaldehyde followed by sodium bisulfite.
A EC 2.4.1.* (hexosyltransferase) inhibitor that inhibits the action of chitin synthase (EC 2.4.1.16).
A polymyxin having a 6-methylheptanoyl group at the amino terminus.
The sulfuric acid salt of colistin A.
The sulfuric acid salt of colistin B.
A class of polyene antifungal antibiotics produced by Streptomyces noursei, and other Streptomyces species.
A family of glycolipids comprising phosphatidylinositol joined to linear chains of beta-(1->2)-linked mannosyl residues.
Any drug which blocks vasopressin receptors.
